answer:
If $[ABC]$ denotes the area of $\triangle ABC$, then $[ABC] = \frac{1}{2} \cdot [AB] \cdot [BC] \cdot \sin(\angle ABC)$.

Draw altitude $\overline{AH}$ from $A$ to $\overline{BC}$.  Let $H$ denote the foot of the altitude.  Then $AH = 6$ and $BH = 4$.  This means $HC = 4$.

[asy]
size(180);
defaultpen(linewidth(.7pt)+fontsize(10pt));
pair A, B, C, D, E, F, H;
A=(0,6);
B=(0,0);
C=(8,0);
D=(0,3);
E=(4,0);
F=(8/3,2);
H=(4,0);
draw(A--B--C--cycle);
draw(A--H);
label("$A(0,6)$", A, W);
label("$B(0,0)$", B, SW);
label("$C(8,0)$", C, S);
label("$D$", D, W);
label("$E$", E, S);
label("$F$", F, SW);
label("$H$", H, dir(270));
draw(rightanglemark(A,H,C,11));
[/asy]

Then $\triangle ABH \sim \triangle HFC$ by AA Similarity.  This means that $$\frac{[AB]}{[HC]} = \frac{[AB]}{[8 - [BH]]} = \frac{[AH]}{[FC]} = \frac{6}{[FC]}.$$Therefore, $[FC] = \frac{2}{3} \cdot [AB]$.  Similarly, $\triangle ABH \sim \triangle BEH$ by AA Similarity, so $$\frac{[AB]}{[BH]} = \frac{[AB]}{4} = \frac{[AH]}{[BE]} = \frac{6}{[BE]}.$$Then $[BE] = 2 \cdot [AB]$.  This means $$[BE] + [FC] = 2 \cdot [AB] + \frac{2}{3} \cdot [AB] = \frac{8}{3} \cdot [AB].$$The area of quadrilateral $DBEF$ is equal to the area of $\triangle ABC$ minus the area of $\triangle BEF$.  This is equal to $$[ABC] - \frac{1}{2} \cdot [BE] \cdot [FC] \cdot \sin(\angle BEF) = \frac{1}{2} \cdot [AB] \cdot [BC] \cdot \sin(\angle ABC) - \frac{1}{2} \cdot \left(\frac{8}{3} \cdot [AB]\right) \cdot \sin(\angle ABC) = \frac{1}{2} \cdot \left(6 - \frac{8}{3}\right) \cdot [AB] \cdot [BC] \cdot \sin(\angle ABC) = \frac{1}{2} \cdot \frac{10}{3} \cdot \frac{1}{2} \cdot 8 \cdot 6 \cdot \sin(90^\circ) = \boxed{20}.$$

