label("$T$",(7,10),N);
label("$R$",(10,0),S);
label("$Q$",(0,0),S);
label("$S$",(15,0),S);
[/asy]

Draw a line $QS$ parallel to $PT$ and $QR$.

Since $QS \parallel PT$ and $PQ$ is a transversal, $\angle PQT$ and $\angle TPQ$ are corresponding angles. Therefore, $\angle PQT = \angle TPQ = x^\circ$.

Since $QS \parallel PT$ and $ST$ is a transversal, $\angle STQ$ and $\angle QTS$ are corresponding angles. Therefore, $\angle STQ = \angle QTS = 2x^\circ$.

The sum of the angles in a triangle is $180^\circ$. Therefore, in $\triangle PQT$,

$$\angle PQT + \angle TPQ + \angle PQT = 180^\circ$$

Substitute the known values,

$$x^\circ + x^\circ + 128^\circ = 180^\circ$$

$$2x^\circ = 52^\circ$$

$$x^\circ = 26^\circ$$

Therefore, $\angle PQR = 180^\circ - \angle PQT - \angle STQ = 180^\circ - x^\circ - 2x^\circ = 180^\circ - 3x^\circ = 180^\circ - 78^\circ = 102^\circ$.The answer is $\boxed{102}$

