label("$A$", A, N);
label("$B$", B, SW);
label("$C$", C, SE);
label("$D$", D, NW);
label("$M$", M, S);
[/asy]

answer:
If $x = \angle BAC,$ then $\angle BDC = 3x.$  Since $AB = AC,$ we have $\angle ACB = \frac{180^\circ - x}{2}.$  Therefore, $3x = 180^\circ - \angle BAC - \frac{180^\circ - x}{2} = \frac{3x}{2} + \frac{180^\circ}{2} = \frac{3x}{2} + 90^\circ,$ so $x = 120^\circ.$

[asy]
unitsize(0.4 cm);

pair A, B, C, D, M;

A = (0,11);
D = (0,1);
B = (-11/2,0);
C = (11/2,0);
M = (B + C)/2;

draw(A--B--C--cycle);
draw(A--M);
draw(B--D--C);

label("$A$", A, N);
label("$B$", B, SW);
label("$C$", C, SE);
label("$D$", D, NW);
label("$M$", M, S);
[/asy]

Note that $\sin 120^\circ = \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}.$  Then $BM = AM \sin 120^\circ = 11 \cdot \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} = \frac{11\sqrt{3}}{2}.$  The Law of Cosines on triangle $ABM$ yields
$$AB = \sqrt{AM^2 + BM^2 - 2 \cdot AM \cdot BM \cos 120^\circ} = \sqrt{11^2 + \left(\frac{11\sqrt{3}}{2}\right)^2 - 2 \cdot 11 \cdot \frac{11\sqrt{3}}{2} \cdot \left(-\frac{1}{2}\right)} = 11\sqrt{3}.$$The perimeter of triangle $ABC$ is $2(11\sqrt{3}) + 2 \cdot \frac{11\sqrt{3}}{2} = \boxed{33\sqrt{3}}.$

