answer:
If $x = \angle BAC,$ then $\angle BDC = 3x.$ Since the altitutde $AM$ is an angle bisector, $BM = MC,$ and $AB = AC.$

[asy]
unitsize(0.4 cm);

pair A, B, C, D, M;

A = (0,11);
D = (0,1);
B = (-11/2,0);
C = (11/2,0);
M = (B + C)/2;

draw(A--B--C--cycle);
draw(A--M);
draw(B--D--C);

label("$A$", A, N);
label("$B$", B, SW);
label("$C$", C, SE);
label("$D$", D, NW);
label("$M$", M, S);
[/asy]

By the Law of Sines on $\triangle BDC,$
$$\frac{BC}{\sin \angle BDC} = \frac{BD}{\sin \angle BCD}.$$Note that $\angle BCD = \angle ACM = \frac{x}{2},$ and $BD = BM - DM = AB \cdot \frac{x}{2\sin x} - 10.$ Thus,
$$\frac{BC}{\sin 3x} = \frac{AB \cdot \frac{x}{2\sin x} - 10}{\sin \frac{x}{2}}.$$By the Law of Sines on $\triangle ABC,$ $\frac{BC}{\sin x} = AB,$ so $BC = AB \sin x.$ Substituting this in and simplifying (using the fact that $\sin 3x = 3 \sin x - 4 \sin^3 x$),
$$\frac{AB \sin x}{3 \sin x - 4 \sin^3 x} = \frac{AB \cdot \frac{x}{2\sin x} - 10}{\sin \frac{x}{2}}.$$

Solving for $AB,$ we find $AB = \frac{11x}{2\sin^2 \frac{x}{2}} = 11 \csc^2 \frac{x}{2}.$ (Note: We used the fact that $\sin x = 2 \sin \frac{x}{2} \cos \frac{x}{2}$ in our solution.)

By the Law of Sines on $\triangle ABM,$ $\frac{AB}{\sin \angle AMB} = \frac{AM}{\sin \angle BAC},$ so $\frac{AB}{1} = \frac{11}{x}.$ Thus, $AB = \frac{11}{x}.$ Equating the two expressions for $AB,$ we get
$$\frac{11}{x} = 11 \csc^2 \frac{x}{2} \implies \sin^2 \frac{x}{2} = \frac{1}{x}.$$Recall that $AB = \frac{11}{x},$ so $x = \frac{11}{AB}.$ Substituting this in and solving the resulting equation for $AB,$ we find $AB = 13.$

[asy]
unitsize(0.4 cm);

pair A, B, C, D, M;

A = (0,11);
D = (0,1);
B = (-11/2,0);
C = (11/2,0);
M = (B + C)/2;

draw(A--B--C--cycle);
draw(A--M);
draw(B--D--C);

label("$A$", A, N);
label("$B$", B, SW);
label("$C$", C, SE);
label("$D$", D, NW);
label("$M$", M, S);
[/asy]

Finally, the perimeter is $13 + 13 + 11 = \boxed{37}.$

