answer:
Isolate $|a|$ to get $|a| = \left|bx + c - (x^2-bx-c)\right|$.By the Triangular Inequality,
$$|a| \le |bx + c| + |x^2 - bx - c|.$$For $0 \le x \le 1$, the maximum value of $|bx + c|$ is $|b| + |c|$.  Similarly, the maximum value of $|x^2 - bx - c|$ is $1 + |b| + |c|$.  Therefore,
$$|a| \le (|b| + |c|) + (1 + |b| + |c|) = 1 + 2(|b| + |c|).$$We can get equality when $bx + c = 1$ and $x^2 - bx - c = 1$ for all $x$.  The first equation forces $b = 0$ and $c = 1$.  But then the second equation is $x^2 - 1 = 1$ for all $x$, which is impossible.

Instead, let $b = -3$, $c = 2$, and $a = 3$.  Then
$$|3x^2 - 3x + 2| = |3x^2 - 3x + 2 - 1 - (3x^2 - 3x + 2)| = |1 - 3x + (-3x + 2)| \le 1$$for all $0 \le x \le 1$.  Hence, we can get $|a| + |b| + |c| = 3 + 3 + 2 = 8$.

The following figure shows that it is impossible to achieve a larger value of $|a| + |b| + |c|$.

[asy]
size(6cm);

path f = (0, 2)--(1/2, 3/4)--(1,2);
path g = (0,1)--(1/2,1/2)--(1,1);

draw(rotate(0)*f, red + 1.4);
draw(rotate(20)*f, red + 1.4);
draw(rotate(40)*f, red + 1.4);
draw(rotate(60)*f, red + 1.4);
draw(rotate(80)*f, red + 1.4);
draw(rotate(100)*f, red + 1.4);
draw(rotate(120)*f, red + 1.4);
draw(rotate(140)*f, red + 1.4);
draw(rotate(160)*f, red + 1.4);

filldraw(rotate(0)*g, red + 1.4);
filldraw(rotate(20)*g, red + 1.4);
filldraw(rotate(40)*g, red + 1.4);
filldraw(rotate(60)*g, red + 1.4);
filldraw(rotate(80)*g, red + 1.4);
filldraw(rotate(100)*g, red + 1.4);
filldraw(rotate(120)*g, red + 1.4);
filldraw(rotate(140)*g, red + 1.4);
filldraw(rotate(160)*g, red + 1.4);

for (int i = 0; i < 17; i += 1) {
  draw((i/16, 1.5) -- (i/16, 2.5), gray(0.5) + dotted);
  draw((0, i/8) -- (1, i/8), gray(0.5) +dotted);
}

draw((0,0)--(0,3), EndArrow);
draw((0,0)--(1,0), EndArrow);

label("$1$", (0,1), W);
label("$2$", (0,2), W);
label("$3$", (0,3), W);
label("$0$", (0.5,-0.2), E);
label("$1$", (1,1), E);
[/asy]The largest possible value is $\boxed{8}$.

